metadata.name: Anarchy #229
metadata.description:
"Anarchy" aims to pay tribute to the Impressionist masters and explore the interplay between randomness and control. My goal was to capture the bold use of color and the fleeting nature of light and movement that is so characteristic of the Abstract Impressionist style. 

This piece uses a total of 12 color palettes, each one inspired by a different Impressionist painter. Some artists have two palette variations, while others only have one.

I wanted to create something that was unique and that would reflect my own visual emotions while also paying homage to the artists that inspire me. "Anarchy" is part of my exploration of the relationship between randomness and intention, and a celebration of the enduring legacy of the Impressionist masters.

Made by wandurz using p5.js 
January 2023

metadata.name: Dualidad #112
metadata.description:
The concept of 'Dualidad' (duality) is brought to life through the use of opposing elements, circles, and rectangles, in the artwork. 

The circles, like the stillness of a calm pond, remain in close places while they continuously transform. In contrast, the rectangles are a representation of movement and change, constantly traveling across the canvas. 

This balance of opposing elements creates a dynamic tension that draws the viewer in, leaving them mesmerized by the ever-evolving artwork. Expect to see a range of emotions, from the euphoria of joy to the depth of sorrow, as you explore the duality of this project.

-----

The generative process of each artwork has a typical completion time ranging from 20 seconds to 2 minutes, depending on your PC.

-----

Tested on Brave, Opera and Mozilla (Linux systems). Brave and Safari (macOS)


-----

Press "e" to save a high res png while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2023)

Made with P5js and <3

metadata.name: Enfold #62
metadata.description:
‚ÄúWe saw the first blossoms late that year, an anticipated promise from the tenacious, etiolated fingers we'd observed making their way through the unseasonable snow; a dirty snow. They represented hope, pushing through this gritty crust formed of equal parts ice and ash making an inevitable descent from the troposphere. We kidded ourselves it was the earth washing itself clean, erasing all evidence of what we'd done, though we knew in our secret hearts that no amount of rainfall, ironically, could save us from the flood.‚Äù

Enfold is a piece based around distance: distance from circles, distance from centres, distance from edges. Points, places and relationships between separate entities are combined and forced through curated palettes of bright and vivid colours, producing overlapping, elliptical and lens-shaped areas formed from emergent, convex arcs.

metadata.name: On the Grid #35
metadata.description:
On the Grid is a generative art project resulting in a unique 16/9 format world map.

This project is inspired by a 114cm x 76cm Lego world map that I created in real life. The coordinates of the continents are transpositions from this first project.

It is made using SVG and Vanilla JS with no libraries.

I hope you enjoy discovering On the Grid and minting your own unique world map.

Thanks for collecting!

In live mode:
- 's': save as PNG (3200√ó1800)
- 'v': save as SVG  
- 'f': open in full screen mode

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #14
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: Meridian #5
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Meridian' attempts to capture some of the beauty and simplicity of Bauhaus design ideas. The addition of a line (or Meridian) to these simple shapes creates a colorful, striking design with an Art Deco vibe!

To download:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.
